      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"10",
        "trailText":"<p>In central London, home visits to repair domestic appliances can be very costly – or difficult to arrange</p>",
        "headline":"Sometimes, and in some places, extended warranties make sense",
        "body":"<p><strong>We note your general advice about the potential cost of extended warranties over the cost of individual repairs. However, in the central London congestion zone, where we live, independent traders are reluctant to accept a commission/call-out unless parking is guaranteed (often impossible), and some say that they do not operate in the congestion zone.</strong></p><p><strong>For most appliances, the issue is getting them working again. We always buy an extended warranty from an insurance company. We find that the premiums, divided by the years of operation, provide an annual cost that is little more than one central London call out – which may include only the first half-hour of work. </strong><em>BS, London</em></p><p>You make a fair point, and as ever each person must decide for themselves whether to buy extended warranties/aftermarket insurance after assessing cost versus likely payback. Clearly, boiler insurance is good value if you have a troublesome unit that requires regular visits, and you live in an area such as yours.</p><p>However, buying a £35 three-year plan for a £60 microwave oven that comes with a one-year guarantee does not, to us, make any sense – irrespective of where you live. Buy the microwave from John Lewis and you now automatically receive a two-year guarantee. Or just buy a replacement as required. In our experience, most electrical products fail quite quickly – within the warranty period – or last for several years. Remember, the Sale of Goods Act covers goods for up to six years in England and Wales, although many retail staff have never heard of this legislation, and we accept that enforcing your rights can be tricky.</p><p><strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418872934|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|3bc399e0d698dd81b7aa92506e792a932f547c03 -->",
