        "trailText":"<p>Halifax turned me down for its Clarity credit card just as others have reported. I can't begin to understand why it has done this</p>",
        "headline":"Halifax quoted Experian for refusing me credit, but my rating is clear",
        "body":"<p><strong>I did a double-take when reading the </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/sep/30/halifax-turned-down-credit-card\" title=\"\"><strong>letter from HC, Walthamstow</strong></a><strong> (Consumer Champions, 28 September) about the problem HC had had trying to apply for a Halifax Clarity credit card. The same thing had happened to me in August. The only difference was that I applied online rather than over the telephone. I was astonished to receive a message saying I'd been turned down, quoting </strong><a href=\"http://www.experian.co.uk/\" title=\"\"><strong>Experian</strong></a><strong>. </strong></p><p><strong>I was quite worried by this as I'd never been refused credit before and knew what a big deal it could be to your credit score. Like HC, when I checked with it, Experian showed my rating to be the highest it could be – with all positive factors and no negative factors.</strong> <em>JF, Ashford, Surrey</em></p><p>It's interesting that your experience mirrors that of last week's reader. Since the card was introduced, we've had a few other letters like these. Earlier this year, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/money/blog/2013/mar/30/money-saving-tips-sting\" title=\"\">Money editor Patrick Collinson was also refused a Halifax Clarity card</a> and like you was concerned that there was a problem with his credit score. Halifax later told him it automatically blocks online applicants who have a basic <a href=\"http://www.halifax.co.uk/bankaccounts/basic-bank-account/\" title=\"\">Halifax Easycash</a> account (which he had used to obtain an Electron card to buy cheap Ryanair flights). It turns out that you had one too, possibly explaining why you were declined. Halifax should be making this clear – if that is still its policy – rather than worrying its customers in this unnecessary way.</p><p><strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418870750|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|2f592ff829d7b7b8c2049f4bd6af5df1a8f1b2df -->",
