        "newspaperPageNumber":"10",
        "trailText":"<p>The Post Office isn't answering its HomePhone customer care line, and doesn't reply to emails</p>",
        "headline":"My relative's Post Office phone is dead, no matter what we do",
        "body":"<p><strong>I wonder if you can help me make progress with the Post Office's HomePhone division. </strong></p><p><strong>A 90-year-old relative of mine who lives near Bakewell in Derbyshire has had no telephone service since the end of August, after his line mysteriously went dead. His service is particularly important as he has a Lifeline emergency system that he can use in the event of a fall. However, it works via the phone line. </strong></p><p><strong>Another relative has plugged in his own handset to test the line, but it is dead. When we try to call the Post Office, we are left hanging on to the 0845 number. I have emailed, as have others, but we have had no response. I have tried alternative numbers on </strong><a href=\"http://www.saynoto0870.com/\" title=\"\"><strong>saynoto0870.com</strong></a><strong> with the same result. I reported the matter to </strong><a href=\"http://consumers.ofcom.org.uk/\" title=\"\"><strong>Ofcom</strong></a><strong>, which gave me a case number, but my relative still has no phone. </strong></p><p><strong>I understand that the Post Office is having \"technical issues\" in upgrading its system. But surely it has an obligation to answer the telephone and to ensure the safety of vulnerable people. I should appreciate your help in bringing this to the attention of somebody senior in the Post Office, and stressing the urgency of this case. </strong><em>JB, Dunster, Somerset</em></p><p>We, too, tried to phone Post Office HomePhone's customer service line and couldn't get through. The Post Office press office proved more responsive. It sent an engineer round to your relative's street and quickly had him reconnected. You have since been told that the unscheduled disconnection was the result of a BT Openreach engineer carrying out maintenance.</p><p>These things happen, but it should be possible to call your phone provider to report problems. This week, the Post Office website was still reporting: \"As a result of changes to our broadband and phone service we are experiencing technical issues which are resulting in calls to our customer care line taking longer than normal to answer. We apologise to customers for any inconvenience and are working hard to rectify this.\"</p><p>We understand that TalkTalk recently took over the provision of the PO's HomePhone service.</p><p><strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418864573|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|d666414219af438f2bd1a67e4c687f4cec911bc4 -->",
