        "headline":"Zurich paid out for spurious accident – and doubled my premium",
        "body":"<p><strong>I have been wrongly accused by Zurich Insurance of being responsible for a car accident last year. </strong></p><p><strong>On 18 June 2012 a man accused me of reversing into him outside my house. I had not, but I called Zurich immediately. It sent a mechanic to inspect both cars and it was deemed I had no case to answer. </strong></p><p><strong>Then, in July, I was contacted by Zurich and told that I had reversed into a car in my street on 22 June 2012. Again this was untrue, but this time no inspections were made and in October I received a letter saying that \"the case has been closed\". </strong></p><p><strong>Naturally I thought that was the end of it. But when I renewed my policy in June 2013 the premium had doubled and I was told it was because of the \"accident\". </strong></p><p><strong>Zurich seems to have paid out the claim without consulting me. It has failed to produce any evidence to support the claim and has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing yet, tellingly, it has reinstated my lost no-claims bonus.</strong> <em>LC, London</em></p><p>This is a case of staggering incompetence on the part of Zurich. Your no-claims bonus was reinstated as a \"gesture of goodwill\", it says, because it realised it could have done more to investigate the second alleged accident.</p><p>Yet this realisation did not prompt it to probe deeper. Only when you contacted Your Problems did Zurich commence \"further investigation\" and, lo,  it discovered that if it had done its job properly last year it may well not have paid out for this spurious claim.</p><p>It has now removed the record of this incident from the Claims and Underwriting Exchange database – used by all insurers when checking claims history – so that your future premiums are not affected. Your renewal premium has been recalculated to reflect this and you are being sent a refund of the difference plus £200 apology.</p><p><strong>If you need help email Anna Tims at </strong><a href=\"mailto:your.problems@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\"><strong>your.problems@observer.co.uk</strong></a><strong> or write to Your Problems, The Observer, Kings Place, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Include an address and phone number.</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418760175|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|64e0ca593220fa3135b51a31637e904b955ee7d5 -->",
