      "id":"money/2013/oct/06/bt-paper-bill-charge-businesses",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-06T05:59:00Z",
      "webTitle":"BT's paper bill charge is penalising small businesses",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/06/bt-paper-bill-charge-businesses",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/oct/06/bt-paper-bill-charge-businesses",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"I need bills for my VAT receipt – but why should I pay £6 a month for them?",
        "headline":"BT's paper bill charge is penalising small businesses",
        "body":"<p><strong>BT has informed me that from November all business customers will be automatically switched to paperless billing for our \"added convenience\", unless we pay £6 a month to keep the status quo. </strong></p><p><strong>Small businesses have to keep records by law and will now be obliged to spend time and effort navigating the BT website, remembering passwords and downloading a copy of something that BT is obliged by law, under VAT regulations, to provide. </strong></p><p><strong>I believe it is illegal to charge for issuing a VAT receipt. Those, like me, who receive a monthly bill are now to face a price increase of £72 a year, in my case a 10% hike. Obviously BT could have elected to email monthly bills to its business customers, which doesn't cost it a penny. </strong></p><p><strong>I haven't seen one word in the media about this latest example of a rip-off charge being levied to add to someone's bottom line. <em> </em></strong><em>JC, Newcastle upon Tyne</em></p><p>\"BT Business isn't forcing customers to go paper-free,\" says a hurt spokeswoman with impenetrable logic, \"because customers can choose to continue with paper bills at a cost of £2 for each summary bill with a VAT statement.</p><p>\"The £6 fee only applies to itemised bills.\"</p><p>Moreover, she denies that it is charging for VAT statements because although, yes, there are those non-coercive fees, customers are being given the privilege of switching to free online billing.</p><p>As for your email solution: \"We email customers to say their bill is ready and include a link so they don't need to find it themselves,\" says the spokeswoman. \"We can't just email the bill for security reasons.\"</p><p>The Federation of Small Businesses echoes your concerns: \"BT's drive to give business customers their bills online could hinder those firms in areas that suffer from poor broadband provision,\" says a spokesperson. \"For those firms that struggle to get online, the charge for a paper bill, £2 or up to £6, could act as a penalty for something out of their control.\"</p><p>According to the telecoms regulator, Ofcom, companies can charge whatever they like because such fees are a \"commercial decision\" and customers who object can always jump ship. It has, however, contacted BT to ask for an explanation of the new charges and how they were communicated to customers.</p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p><strong>If you need help email Anna Tims at </strong><a href=\"mailto:your.problems@observer.co.uk\" title=\"\"><strong>your.problems@observer.co.uk</strong></a><strong> or write to Your Problems, The Observer, Kings Place, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Include an address and phone number.</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418762299|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|8fdcf1f3035f8eb0bfd3718a3b89b96517d0b641 -->",
