        "newspaperPageNumber":"10",
        "trailText":"<p>My stolen car was found, but Direct Line claims Volkswagen's failure to supply spares is why I'm yet to get it back</p>",
        "headline":"Thieves had my car for weeks. Direct Line has had it for months",
        "body":"<p><strong>I am at my wits' end trying to get my </strong><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2012/jun/15/vw-up-1-litre-60-review\" title=\"\"><strong>Volkswagen Up</strong></a><strong> back from my insurer, Direct Line, after the vehicle was recovered in mid July, following its theft at the end of May. For the past two months the car has been at Direct Line's nominated garage waiting for the locks to be replaced.</strong></p><p><strong>It has been hugely inconvenient to be without a car for so long, and nothing seems to be happening to get me back on the road.</strong></p><p><strong>While Direct Line's staff have been pleasant, I have felt that the person managing all this was me, not the insurer. I have had to make numerous 0845 calls to progress matters. Direct Line is blaming a lack of parts from VW. Can this really be the case? </strong><em>TR, Hampton, Middlesex</em></p><p>Direct Line is normally pretty good after a claim, but it could have managed this better. It says it did not get clearance from the police, who wanted to fingerprint the car, until the middle of August, but why it took a month for this to happen is unclear.</p><p>Direct Line says that as soon as it gained access it sent a repairer and that a set of new locks were ordered the following day. The locks have not turned up because of delays at VW, it says.</p><p>One problem you've encountered is that courtesy or replacement cars are not generally offered in the event of a theft. Getting parts for modern cars also seems to be an increasing problem, according to our postbag. We have suggested that between Direct Line and VW it should be possible to find a car to lend you, and VW has now offered you a courtesy car and is tracking the part delivery in an attempt to minimise further delays.</p><p>Direct Line told us: \"While we sympathise with TR, the delays have been out of our control and we are in contact with VW to resolve this matter. However, as a gesture of goodwill for the inconvenience caused by these delays, we will be sending [TR] a cheque for £75.\" While £75 is better than nothing, all TR wants is his car back. Speed up, VW.</p><p><strong>We welcome letters but cannot answer individually. Email us at </strong><a href=\"mailto:consumer.champions@theguardian.com\" title=\"\"><strong>consumer.champions@theguardian.com</strong></a><strong> or write to Consumer Champions, Money, the Guardian, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Please include a daytime phone number</strong></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418867219|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|ae3737b7a7e4b40af9b7eb99259d249ce7beb03a -->",
