      "id":"money/2013/oct/05/married-couples-tax-break-transfer-allowance",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-05T06:00:13Z",
      "webTitle":"Married couples tax break … for richer for poorer",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/05/married-couples-tax-break-transfer-allowance",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/oct/05/married-couples-tax-break-transfer-allowance",
      "fields":{
        "newspaperPageNumber":"6",
        "trailText":"Married couples and civil partners will be able to transfer £1,000 of their tax allowance to their partner – but it could actually mean a pay cut for some",
        "headline":"Married couples tax break … for richer for poorer",
        "body":"<p>The <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2013/sep/27/tory-tax-break-marriage-glue\" title=\"Tories woo married couples with tax break\">recently announced married couple's tax break</a> will benefit few people and may even make some worse off after a pay rise, according to an <a href=\"http://www.ifs.org.uk/publications/6869\" title=\"IFS analysis\">analysis by the Institute for Fiscal Studies</a> (IFS).</p><p>Robert Joyce, a senior research economist at the institute, says: &quot;The policy is not a general recognition of marriage in the income tax system … it is difficult to escape the conclusion that an income tax system which makes some people worse off after a pay rise has something wrong with it.&quot;</p><p>So how exactly will the new allowance work, what is it worth to couples – and how could it actually be detrimental to you?</p><p></p><h2><strong>What has the prime minister proposed?</strong></h2><p>The plan is to make up to &pound;1,000 of a person's income tax personal allowance transferable between adults who are married or in a civil partnership, so long as the higher income adult is a basic rate taxpayer.</p><p>For example, let's say a man earns &pound;30,000 and his wife earns &pound;6,000 a year working part time. She has a <a href=\"https://www.gov.uk/income-tax-rates\" title=\"Personal Allowance explained \">personal allowance</a>, expected to be &pound;10,230 in the year the policy is introduced, but is not using it all. She can transfer &pound;1,000 of this to her husband, lowering his tax bill by up to &pound;200 a year because he'll now not have to pay 20% tax on that &pound;1,000. This saving works out at &pound;3.85 per couple per week.</p><p>But the value of the allowance tapers out once the lower earner starts earning more. For example, if the transfer was allowed to take place today when the personal allowance is &pound;9,440, someone earning &pound;9,000 would only be able to transfer the remaining &pound;440 of their allowance to their spouse before they hit the personal tax allowance threshold. This would give the couple a gain of &pound;88 a year, or just &pound;1.69 a week.</p><p>The scheme will come into force in April 2015, a month before the next general election is expected.</p><p>Couples will be able to apply online and will receive the benefit for the 2015-16 tax year in the summer of&nbsp;2016.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Who will gain?</strong></h2><p>Couples who will qualify for this tax break are those in marriages or civil partnerships, which according to the government should be more than 4 million couples, although the IFS suggests the number may be significantly less – about 3.4 million of the UK's 12.4 million couples who are either married or in a civil partnership. This includes 1.2 million of the 7.8 million families with children.</p><p></p><h2><strong>Who won't gain?</strong></h2><p>Three sorts of couples in a marriage or civil partnership will not be eligible for the tax cut:</p><p>• those whose members both have incomes below the &pound;10,230 personal allowance. They would pay no income tax so cannot benefit from any income tax cut.</p><p>• those where both partners have incomes above the personal allowance.</p><p>• those with a higher rate 40% or additional-rate 45% taxpayer, ie those with taxable incomes exceeding &pound;42,285 a year in 2015-16.</p><p>It is also expected that the shrinking number of couples who still receive the old-style married couples allowance (available only where one spouse or civil partner was born before 6 April 1935), which reduces a couple's tax liability by up to &pound;750 a year as opposed to &pound;200 a year under the proposed tax break, will not be able to claim both.</p><p></p><h2>How could some people be worse off?</h2><p>The IFS says that since the new tax break will not be available to higher rate taxpayers, someone who is benefiting from a transferred personal allowance would have a weaker incentive to increase their taxable income beyond &pound;42,285, the threshold above which income tax at&nbsp;40% kicks in.</p><p>Joyce says: &quot;Some could be worse off after a pay rise or better off after a pay cut, because the transferred allowance will be withdrawn in &quot;cliff edge&quot; fashion – withdrawn in its entirety once income rises above a threshold rather than tapered away gradually. Income tax liability would jump by &pound;200 a year when someone's taxable income crossed &pound;42,285, hence post-tax income would be higher if the taxable income were just below this threshold rather than if it was just above it.&quot;</p><p></p><h2><strong>Isn't this &quot;cliff&quot; similar to the child benefit proposals?</strong></h2><p>Yes, at the 2010 Conservative conference the party announced a similar cliff-edge at the higher rate tax threshold as a way of effectively means-testing child benefit payments, but that was eventually removed and replaced with a less egregious taper at the 2012 budget.</p><p>&quot;The amounts involved here are less than in that case, which perhaps explains the willingness to cliff-edge again rather than implement a taper,&quot; Joyce says. &quot;</p><p></p><h2>Will t<strong>his really encourage more people to marry?</strong></h2><p><strong> </strong></p><p>With a maximum gain of less than &pound;4 per couple per week, the change is not in itself expected to prompt many people to marry rather than live together.</p><p>&quot;The social message sent by the tax break looks more significant than its financial consequences for families, as the prime minister has stated himself,&quot; the IFS says. &quot;But as a structural change to the tax system it may ultimately turn out to be more important.&quot;</p><p>First, the IFS points out, it would reintroduce an incentive to marry into the income tax system, just as the married couple's allowance is being almost entirely phased out.</p><p>Second, the transferral of allowances between spouses would reintroduce an element of joint income taxation, clashing with the move to individual taxation for couples introduced in 1990.</p><p></p><h2><strong>What will all this cost?</strong></h2><p>The IFS estimates that the proposal will cost the exchequer about &pound;700m a year. The precise cost will depend on how many eligible couples use the tax break.</p><p>It is expected that couples will have to make an active claim to take up the offer, so it is therefore likely that take-up will be less than 100% among those who are eligible.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/418832553|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|01199fd74aef4542a7843c25fbb0831153cb8344 -->",
