      "id":"money/2013/oct/04/buying-baby-monitor-guide",
      "sectionId":"money",
      "sectionName":"Money",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-04T14:32:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Buying a baby monitor: a guide",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/money/2013/oct/04/buying-baby-monitor-guide",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/money/2013/oct/04/buying-baby-monitor-guide",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p>From audio-only to motion sensors and video, buying a baby monitor takes a bit of research</p>",
        "headline":"Buying a baby monitor: a guide",
        "body":"<p>Baby monitors are on the shopping lists of many prospective parents. Ellie Weston of parenting website <a href=\"http://www.netmums.com/\" title=\"Netmums website\">Netmums</a> says they are not a necessity, but \"can be a reassuring ear to those who would feel anxious without one\". Weston says she used a baby monitor as a first time mum, but second time around did without one.</p><p>Rebecca, a mum of two, has one with a sensor pad: \"It gives us peace of mind as to what is going on in the room, and as I don't like a silent house in the daytime I may have the radio on so will not necessarily hear my child in another room without a monitor. Also, it can be useful if my child is having bad dreams at night as we can hear them.\"</p><p>Whether you opt for a monitor or not, you might want to download <a href=\"http://www.lullabytrust.org.uk/safer-sleep\" title=\"Lullabny Trust: guide to safe sleeping\">the Lullaby Trust's guides to safer sleep for babies</a>.</p><h2>The choices</h2><p>Monitors tend to consist of two units: one device in the baby's room and one for wherever the parent is, allowing them to listen to or even see the baby. Broadly there are three main types.</p><p><strong>Audio device</strong> This is the most familiar type of monitor. There is a transmitter in the child's room which broadcasts the sound to a receiver, allowing  you to hear your baby.</p><p><strong>Audio with motion sensor pads</strong> As well as the transmitter you get a sensor mat, which you place under the baby and plug into the unit in his or her room. If the baby does not move for a certain period of time an alarm sounds on the receiver.</p><p><strong>Video monitors</strong> These come with a small camera which you put in the child's room and allow you to watch your baby as well as being able to hear them. Many have night vision so work even with the lights off. Some new monitors offer remote access enabling you to watch your baby on a computer, tablet or smartphone when you are away from home.</p><p>Other useful additional features many monitors include are a room temperature gauge, sound-sensitive light display that illuminates more as the baby moves around, a nightlight, the ability to play lullabies, an \"out of range\" warning signal, a battery indicator and a \"talk-back\" facility, allowing you to speak to your baby.</p><p>You also have a choice of how the monitor transmits:</p><p><strong>Analogue</strong> These are becoming a rare breed. They can pick up other signals, sometimes broadcasting sounds from radios and other monitors. However they are generally the cheapest models.</p><p><strong>Digital</strong> These provide clearer sound than analogue, typically with less interference.</p><p><strong>Digitally enhanced cordless telecommunications (DECT)</strong> These are designed to make it less likely that you will hear anyone else's baby or neighbours' conversations.</p><h2>Other considerations</h2><p>Although you can buy mains powered-only monitors, it is more useful to have one that also runs on batteries – mains-only restricts you to one room and won't work if there is a power cut.</p><p>After buying, test out the product for suitability. The thickness of your walls and size of your house can affect the sound and range of the device. And beware, advertised ranges often are the maximum possible given perfect conditions. Test the product for interference from radios, phones and other nearby devices as well.</p><p>Weston says if you are buying a monitor \"make sure it is easy to use, chargeable with good battery life, and not too expensive.\"</p><h2>The monitors</h2><p>Below are the best prices for some popular models, but prices can change rapidly so please put any better deals you spot in the comments section below. It is worth noting that if you are spending more than £100, Mothercare is offering online purchasers a further 15% off until Monday 7 October.</p><p><strong>Audio only </strong>The Tommee Tippee Closer to Nature 1082 has an intercom, room temperature monitor and nightlight, and according to the Which? \"best buy\" list \"works exceptionally well as you move around the house\". It costs as much as £64.99 elsewhere, but <a href=\"http://www.toysrus.co.uk/Babies-R-Us/Safety/Monitors-and-Nightlights/Tommee-Tippee-Closer-To-Nature-Digital-Monitor%280085613%29?searchPosition=3\" title=\"Babies R Us monitor deal\">can be found at Babies R Us for £40.49</a>.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419094030'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2013/10/4/1380888679232/BT-Baby-Monitor-250-001.jpg' alt='BT Baby Monitor 250' width='220' height='141' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>BT Baby Monitor 250</figcaption></figure><p>The BT Baby Monitor 250 with digital sound has a 50m range indoors and 300m outdoors, and has an \"out of range\" warning signal. It can play eight different lullabies and has a temperature monitor and a \"talk back\"' feature. <a href=\"http://www.argos.co.uk/static/Search/searchTerms/BT+BABY+MONITOR+250.htm\" title=\"Argos monitor deal\">Argos</a>, <a href=\"http://www.johnlewis.com/bt-baby-monitor-250/p231141260\" title=\"John Lewis monitor deal\">John Lewis</a> and <a href=\"http://www.mothercare.com/BT-250-Digital-Baby-Monitor/366180,default,pd.html#q=bt%20monitor\" title=\"Mothercare monitor deal\">Mothercare</a> are all offering £20 off the RRP and selling it for £49.99.</p><p><strong>Movement and audio </strong>The Angelcare Movement and Sound Monitor AC401 alerts you if your baby is still for 20 seconds. The sensor pad has a number of sensitive settings, but does not work on memory foam mattresses. The mobile parent unit is rechargeable and has an \"out of range\" alarm. The RRP is £99.99, but there are a few retailers charging £66.50, including <a href=\"http://www.mothercare.com/Angelcare-Movement-and-Sound-Monitor-AC401/994539,default,pd.html#q=angelcare\" title=\"Mothercare monitor deal\">Mothercare</a> and <a href=\"http://www.toysrus.co.uk/Babies-R-Us/Safety/Monitors-and-Nightlights/Angelcare-AC401-Movement-and-Sound-Baby-Monitor%280030643%29?searchPosition=0\" title=\"Babies R Us monitor deal\">Babies R Us</a>. However, <a href=\"http://www.savoo.co.uk/m-Tesco-Direct-vouchers.html?searchString=tesco+direct\" title=\"Savoo monitor code\">Savoo</a> currently has a code that gives you a further £10 off at <a href=\"http://www.tesco.com/direct/angelcare-sound-movement-baby-monitor-ac401/203-9708.prd?pageLevel=&amp;skuId=203-9708&amp;sc_cmp=pcp_GSF_Baby%20Safety_203-9708&amp;icid=spiffy_angelcare_203-9708_angelc\" title=\"Tesco monitor deal\">Tesco Direct</a> if it is your first shop, reducing the price to £56.50.</p><figure data-media-id='gu-image-419094031'><img src='http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Money/Pix/pictures/2013/10/4/1380888879291/Tomy-TDV450-monitor-001.jpg' alt='Tomy TDV450 monitor' width='220' height='129' class='gu-image'/><figcaption>Tomy TDV450 monitor</figcaption></figure><p><strong>Video monitors</strong> The Tomy TDV450 digital video baby monitor has a 3.5-inch colour display and infra-red night vision, so you can see your child even when it is dark. It also has two-way talkback and a nightlight. <a href=\"http://www.babymonitorsdirect.co.uk/products/189/Tomy-TDV450-Baby-Video-Monitor-3.5%22.html\" title=\"Baby Monitors Direct monitor deal\">Baby Monitors Direct offers the best price at £99.50</a>, making one major retailer look extremely expensive at £169.99.</p><p>The Tommee Tippee Closer to Nature Video Sensor baby monitor has a 3-inch colour screen and a movement sensor pad so you can hear, see and be alerted if there is no movement detected after 20 seconds. You can buy this via the Savoo code mentioned above at <a href=\"http://www.tesco.com/direct/tommee-tippee-closer-to-nature-video-sensor-baby-monitor/214-3377.prd?pageLevel=&amp;skuId=214-3377\" title=\"Tesco monitor deal\">Tesco Direct for £120</a> if it is your first shop, otherwise it is £130 there or with <a href=\"http://www.toysrus.co.uk/Babies-R-Us/Safety/Monitors-and-Nightlights/Tommee-Tippee-Closer-to-Nature-Video-Move-Monitor%280094991%29?searchPosition=1\" title=\"Babies R Us monitor deal\">Babies R Us</a>.</p><p>Do you have a baby monitor you rate or tips for those who are about to buy one? Please add your thoughts below.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419064587|2013-10-07T10:05:57Z|ac0dab0798520aba1ffd230ee14be693005b5178 -->",
